title: [TVM EP] Build on Windows with ipp-crypto support
body:
**Description**:
- CMake files was updated for build external project ipp-crypto on Windows.
- TVM_EP.md was updated.

**Motivation and Context**
- Intel ipp-crypto is used by TVM EP for supporting of handshake mechanism which allows to match onnx model and performance library obtained for it.
- Intel ipp-crypto has some specifics for build on Windows which does not allow to build it together with ORT project. Particularly it strongly uses NASM compiler for .asm files, the compiler conflicts with default one used for ORT.

title: The Clone Session interface is expected
body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
I'm going to dynamically add and create sessions on what's happening online, deal with the sudden increase in requests.
`Ort::Env`, `Ort::SessionOptions`, and  `void* model_data` must be required when creating seesion for the same model.
Whether to add a Clone interface on Ort::Session ï¼Ÿ 
example: `std::unique_ptr<Ort::Session> new_session = session.Clone();`

If this interface is not available, there are several problems:
1. When I want to create an new Ort::Session  that is identical to an existing session, I must save the previous Ort::SessionOptions and mode_data. When the model is large, saving model_data incurs additional memory growth.
2. f the Clone interface is implemented, memory optimizations between Ort::Sessions (e.g. Share allocator, Share initializer, Share ORT pre-processed ...) could be done internally. The user can easily select the optimization through the configuration, and without having to write a lot of codes for complex optimizations.

**System information**
- ONNX Runtime version (you are using):1.11.1

**Describe the solution you'd like**
Add a `Clone` interface on Ort::Session.
example: `std::unique_ptr<Ort::Session> new_session = session.Clone()`

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
A clear and concise description of any alternative solutions or features you've considered.

title: unsafe exception code in C++ API, wrongly declaring exceptions, incomplete constructors
body:
The C++ api for onnx is unsafe in its exception handling. I see no less than 21 places in which exceptions are incorrectly handled which likely leads to crashes. _Most concerning_ is `The function is declared 'noexcept' but calls function 'xxxxxxx()' which may throw exceptions (f.6).`. These are locations in which the compiler won't put necessary code to catch exceptions yet called code might still throw...resulting in undefined behavior and nothing good ðŸ’¥

### Setup

* Microsoft Windows [Version 10.0.19044.1826]
* VS2019 community v16.11.17
* onnx 1.12.0 via nuget `<package id="Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.DirectML" version="1.12.0" />`

### Repro

```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <onnxruntime_cxx_api.h>

void do_onnx() {
    auto ep = Ort::GetAvailableProviders();
    for (const auto& one : ep) {
        std::cerr << one << std::endl;
    }
}
```

1. compile with `/analyze:plugin EspXEngine.dll` and envvar `esp.extensions=CppCoreCheck.dll`

dozens of warnings and errors of unsafe code, incomplete code, etc. See log below.

Clean compile. No errors or warnings from onnx codebase

title: fused conv dimension fix
body:
**Description**:
- In Cuda EP, op `FusedConv`, when `Y` dimension is changed, also change the `Z` dimension to match.

**Motivation and Context**
- Fixes CUDNN error in `FusedConv` when `Z` dimension does not match `Y` dimension. This can happen when `Y` dimension is automatically changed. Eg Z is [1, 1024, 16] whereas Y is [1, 1024, 16, 1]
- Fixes [[11548](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/11548)](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/12321), https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/11548, and https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/9194
- The fix is as follow:
  - When `Y` dim is changed, try to match `Z` dim by:
  - Checking if `z_dim` is 1 less than `y_dim` and the last dimension of `Y` is 1; if true, add last `y_dim[-1]` to `z_dim`
  - Then check every dimension of `Y` and `Z` matches, return error before attempting CUDNN calls.

title: .to(dtype, device) causes runtime error
body:
### Bug description
'to' function is failing when we invoke using the below function call, where both dtype and device are passed in as arguments.

```
cpu_zeros = torch.zeros(128, 128)
cpu_zeros.to(dtype=torch.bfloat16, device=...) # this fails
```

If we separate them out as unique calls, it passes successfully i.e Data Transfer from host to device is successful and then cast operation is performed.
`cpu_zeros.to(device=...).to(dtype=torch.bfloat16) # this works`

The root cause is that DataTransfer to NPU is skipped in the failing case. On further investigation, it is found that the pytorch/onnxruntime function calls are identical in the passing and the failing case, until the scalar_type check in onnxruntime/orttraining/orttraining/eager/ort_aten.cpp

Within copy_ function, there is a check for scalar type of self and src.
In passing case, the scalar type is matching for self and src, and the data transfer from host to device is invoked.
Passing case has self and src as Float and hence data transfer is successful and later cast is called.

```
0x00007fff7b75a1af in torch_ort::eager::aten::copy_ (self=..., src=..., non_blocking=false)    at /onnxruntime.git/orttraining/orttraining/eager/ort_aten.cpp:482
copy(invoker, ort_src, ort_self);
(gdb) p self.scalar_type()$1 = c10::ScalarType::Float
(gdb) p src.scalar_type()$2 = c10::ScalarType::Float
```

In the failing case, we are entering the scalar type mismatch case, hence cast operation is performed first without doing the data transfer. Failing case has this mismatch

```
0x00007fff7b759d7e in torch_ort::eager::aten::copy_ (self=..., src=..., non_blocking=false) 
onnxruntime/onnxruntime.git/orttraining/orttraining/eager/ort_aten.cpp:471
(gdb) p self.scalar_type()
$6 = c10::ScalarType::BFloat16
(gdb) p src.scalar_type()
$7 = c10::ScalarType::Float
```
The issue is that self.scalarType should not be BFloat16 at this point. It should be Float as well, so that we proceed with the Datatransfer from host to device.

### Urgency
Not a blocking issue since the separate .to() calls work

### System information
- OS Platform and Distribution Linux Ubuntu 20.04
- ONNX Runtime version: e8b0d2407157216a898d0575cf6fe03df6ece389
- Python version: 3.8.10
- GCC/Compiler version: GCC 9.4.0

### To Reproduce
- Use this sample code to reproduce the issue locally.
```
cpu_zeros = torch.zeros(128, 128)
cpu_zeros.to(dtype=torch.bfloat16, device=...) # this fails
```

### Expected behavior
Datatransfer from host to device should be performed first and then cast should be called.

The benefit of writing out cache at inference session destructor is not a good solution in sever scenario such as Triton.  
Because server might be crashed before inference session destructor is called and end up with no cache being saved.
Also, this engine refactoring makes our customers need to modify the production code, so we decide to revert to old behavior for now.

OnDeviceTraining=True property to MSBuild, or by setting it to true in the following:
csharp\src\Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime\Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.csproj
csharp\test\Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.Tests.NetCoreApp\Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.Tests.NetCoreApp.csproj

title: CUDA kernel for ClipGradNorm for TensorSeq gradients

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
Currently, `ClipGradNorm` in `onnxruntime` is executed by running more primitive onnxruntime ops followed by a `SequenceConstruct` before feeding into `AdamWOptimizer`. 

This `SequenceConstruct` will create another copy of the input tensors and put them into a `TensorSeq`. To avoid making these copies, the `ClipGradNorm` kernel can take in a `TensorSeq` and clip the gradients in place.

title: QuickGelu Fusion

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
Some models have QuickGelu(x)=x*sigmoid(1.702x), which has 3 Ops for forward and 5 Ops for backward. The PR is to fuse this to a single Op named QuickGelu and its gradient QuickGeluGrad.

For CUDA, tested in V100 using input tensor with shape [64,128,2048] and float16 type:
Before, FW takes 335us, BW takes 614us
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/11661208/182291335-15188709-ffe7-44d1-9d14-0b544cbe5e55.png)

After, FW takes 115us, BW takes 139us, which is much faster.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/11661208/182291502-f0b5161c-b95c-45fc-90f8-ad0c592d2433.png)

For CPU kernel, using same shape and float type:
Before, FW takes 10us, BW takes 49us
Mul: 3480[Âµs]
Sigmoid: 1996[Âµs]
Mul: 4789[Âµs]
Mul: 4642[Âµs]
Mul: 4195[Âµs]
SigmoidGrad: 18328[Âµs]
Mul: 2988[Âµs]
Sum: 18576[Âµs]

After, FW takes 4us, BW takes 5us, which is also much faster.
QuickGelu: 3939[Âµs]
QuickGeluGrad: 5089[Âµs]

title: Fix include order build failure training build
body:
This fixes build fatal error c1083: Cannot open include file 'safeint/SafeInt.hpp'

This build error showed up when building the oneDNN execution provider with --enable_training

Using `git bisect` the issue was issolated to 75bda9f267382e59393250344248438e82a4ad15
Author: pengwa <pengwa@microsoft.com> CPU AdamW implementation (#11978)

After verifying the build without --enable_training was not failing the include paths
were investigated.

I discovered that `core/providers/cpu/tensor/utils.h` has different includes depending
if the macro `SHARED_PROVIDER` is defined.  The only place the macro `SHARED_PROVIDER`
is defined is inside `core/providers/shared_library/provider_api.h` this lead me to
conclude that the `tensor/utils.h` was being included by the build before `provider_api.h`

I forced a build with `SHARED_PROVIDER` defined and verified the include file error did
not occur if `SHARED_PROVIDER` was defined at the start of the build.

The include order build failure was resolved by moving the #include for the `tensor/utils.h`
from adamwbase.h into adamw.h.  This made it so `provider_api.h` was seen before
`tensor/utils.h` resulting in the SHARED_PROVIDER being defined.

Signed-off-by: George Nash <george.nash@intel.com>
